title: Jah Rastiexus - Ode to Pain
description:
o backpain
o whoa-sum low-sum pain
you are the bitter pitter patter 
of palp-able precipitation

prescott the lawyer 
or the kingly saint they sold
ochre liquid to 
and not just any embers of light
not just justin of patua
of street corners mixed with light
and edited without fright 
or loss of disemboweled ideas 

and entrails of friendly stringent 
academically oriented gastronomical eloquence

will you respect me 
or will you recollect me as a dupe?

a hulk
a floral despot
a tiny ampersand without a face

a brick laying a forgotten hindrance 
long assimilated 
but not now unseemingly making an appearance
fashionably on time
right on the mountain 
the raggedy assassin shapes

fate will take trite cake
it took a rook 
from my pawn's bishop's 
battle with a hook
got a captain's engine 
with a lasso and a book

nabokov's illiterate 
windshield wiper of a novel 
grisham's last hour: 
"my dagger pierces his forehead 
and blood oozes out 
and smiles 
upon my wicked soul"

trot trot trickle in a pot 
and i'll eat you grisham 
grish your guts and nab your hat 

or was that the prequel? 
or are you my dreamy crush of a groom? 

fifty-one fractured minds 
begotten to the lost unidentified cause of pain

on the left and traveling upwards
spherically and obliquely

delivering eulogies to euclid
a lacquer-loving tristan tzara 
shucking oyster-licking genre painting 

embalmed in fresh flowing ink 
of pebbles in shanghai rivers
marooned in hong kong
a castle of our towering friendship 
forever expanding into a bleak frozen ocean

title: The Moneyed Mind ‚Äî How Capitalism is Fundamental to Thought
description:

_________

The thesis of this essay is that capitalism is fundamental to thought itself, rather than a contingent oddity we can slide past. The running metaphor throughout is borrowed from Marx; his description of circulation as an alchemical retort which transforms everything into the money crystal.

Its begins with the philosophical battle between thinkers like David Graeber and Friedrich Nietzsche who tried to determine the nature of buying and selling. This is followed by a detailed look at Graeber's claims regarding the egalitarian nature of the Inuit, arguing that the evidence is in Nietzsche's favour. 

After a short summary of the parallels between capitalist exploitation and the function of our bodies, the rest of the essay looks at the so-called 'human crystal' retort, which is often offered as a stark contrast to capitalism, but which has similar logic and pitfalls.

title: Healthy Modern Art and Degenerate Nihilism
description:
ùêÖùêÆùê•ùê• ùêìùêûùê±ùê≠: 

https://andreigeorgescu.ca/healthy-modern-art-and-degenerate-nihilism/

ùêÄùêõùê¨ùê≠ùê´ùêöùêúùê≠

This essay outlines a vision of healthy modern art at by looking at symptoms of illness and signs of recovery. It begins with the prevailing view‚ÄîUgly Duckling Aesthetic Philosophy (UDAP). UDAP can be summarised by the Disney cartoon of its namesake, which teaches that an ugly duckling in one perspective is a beautiful swan to another‚Äîall art is valid expression. Nature tends to disagree, e.g., infanticide of baby swans (cygnets) that can‚Äôt keep up. This kind of brutality is reserved for bullies and fascists‚Äîconsider Nazi Germany and their attack on modern art in their Degenerate Art Exhibit. A positive aesthetic philosophy is sketched out by pointing to the Greco-Roman Spirit. A great example of this spirit is the Laoco√∂n group, reminiscent of Nietzsche‚Äôs concept of the Olympian divine order of joy growing out of the Titanic divine order of terror.

There are indications that mental illness is pervasive‚Äîsome surveys find major depressive disorders spiking among our youth. Here, Max Nordau is useful to make sense of cultural degeneracy. Although Nordau criticizes Nietzsche‚Äôs approach in Zarathustra, Nietzsche‚Äôs observation on the death of God and the spread of nihilism closely matches the observation of Nordau. By examining the politics and philosophy behind a new public sculpture in Toronto, we can more clearly see the decline and illness of modern art.

To offer more context, this essay talks about the Degenerate Art exhibit and the philosophy behind it. First we see an example of Paul Klee and someone institutionalized with schizophrenia, along with Max Beckmann‚Äôs work which shows despair and mental degeneration. This is the kind of disturbance that the Nazis tried to eradicate, and their general brutality has led to generations of punishment for anyone associated‚Äîthe art museum built by the Nazis has had a row of trees planted to obscure its portico.

This kind of vengeance is challenged by looking at one of its casualties, namely Arno Breker. His work has been described as ranking among the greatest of the 20th century, although most of his art has been destroyed and suppressed. The moral panic surrounding Nazi art is fleshed out by looking at critiques from art historians like Elizabeth Berkowitz. The 1993 documentary Degenerate Art which features Robert Hughes is also looked at critically along with a review of Breker‚Äôs aesthetic philosophy. I argue that Breker demonstrates the sort of healthy-minded aesthetic philosophy that satisfies both Zionists like Max Nordau and vicious anti-Semites like Adolph Hitler. Such bipartisan agreement is looked at in more detail, by quoting from Nordau‚Äôs book The Conventional Lies of Civilization and Adolph Hitler‚Äôs Mein Kampf.

As an example of the greatest living modern artist, this essay looks to Cristiano Ronaldo, whose photos fulfill both Zionist and Nazi ideals of beauty‚Äîconsider the Reich Association of Large Families and their criteria for ‚Äòartistically exemplary representations of genetically healthy families with many children‚Äò. Finally, I look at forbidden modern art and the controversy surrounding ‚Äòcomputer generated art‚Äô, followed by an explanation of what constitutes degenerate art and how it can be fought.

title: The Happy Wageslave
description:
This essay seeks to answer the question: can a ‚Äòwageslave‚Äô be happy? 

It begins with an introduction to the antiwork movement and its corollary tensions in ancient thought; the infamous Jesse Watters video interview is discussed alongside Aristophanes and his caricature of philosophers. After tying in Nietzsche‚Äôs reflections on work in The Greek State, there‚Äôs an extended analysis of Aristotle‚Äôs views on slavery, along with the perspective of former American slaves like Frederick Douglass and contemporary business magnates like Kevin O‚ÄôLeary. 

Aristotle, Theognis and Socrates offer their perspective on the physiognomy of slaves, which are compared to contemporary examples of physiognomic discrimination. The work of Italian Renaissance artist Domenico Ghirlandaio is examined as a hopeful cultural icon, and Nietzsche‚Äôs concept of the ‚Äògreat spirit‚Äô is introduced, with King Philip II offered as an example. Modern research on popular psychology is covered and contrasted with Nietzsche's claims about workers, and the case is made that wageslaves can, on the whole, find many opportunities for happiness‚Äîthough it requires certain difficult sacrifices. The essay concludes with reflections on modern thinkers like Jordan Peterson and the role of Christianity in the modern worker‚Äôs life.

Full text: https://andreigeorgescu.ca/the-happy-wageslave/

title: The Audience is a God: Theological Implications of the Spectator
description:
The thesis of this video is that an audience is, functionally speaking, a god‚Äîa sense of physiological & psychological vitality projected onto an external symbol that provides meaning in life. Nietzsche makes the observation that gods serve as a necessary spectator; the Christians sublimate suffering by seeing it as a path to salvation in the eyes of an 'honor-craving' all-seeing eye, while the pagans see the human drama as a heroic, theatrical spectacle for the divine. After looking at the etymology of the term, this video looks at the link between at the most important role of gods in human life‚Äîto make sense of senseless suffering. The Christian amelioration of suffering is analyzed through The Martyrdom of St. Erasmus by Dierc Bouts, followed by practical examples of the belief in a spectator god. The importance of ritual and behaviour‚Äîthe functional dimension of belief‚Äîis discussed alongside its disavowal. Finally, a historic example that corroborates this perspective is reviewed, specifically the ancient Celts.

title: The Necessity of Objectifying People
description:
The thesis of this video is that objectifying people is a necessary and fundamental feature of life. It begins with a critique of the Kantian position, followed by a close look at the etymological roots of object & subject. Nietzsche's speculations on the origin of responsibility and its cruel nature is explored, along with the theory of language as a weapon proposed in the Dialogue of the Dogs by Cervantes. 

'The Deceitful Marriage' is also summarized and put forward as more unflattering but realistic depiction of objectification. The vindictive and sadistic elements of life is looked at through the lens of feminist thinkers like Simone de Beauvoir and Nancy Bauer, with a critical perspective on modern 'empowerment' narratives that center around female objectification. Then, Nietzsche's theory on forgetfulness is analyzed to shed light on his idea that autonomy and morality are mutually exclusive. 

Finally, the work of YouTuber Kevin Samuels is explored as an honest perspective on objectification, followed by concluding remarks that look at the life-projects of thinkers like Nietzsche and Machiavelli.

title: Nietzsche and the Black Panthers
description:
Full text: https://andreigeorgescu.ca/nietzsche-and-the-black-panthers/

Abstract: This video explores the influence Nietzsche had on Huey Newton, the co-founder of The Black Panther Party. Newton was particularly inspired by The Genealogy of Morals, which he used as practical advice to instigate a form of psychological warfare to support his socialist political project. Newton's choice of the group's name is analyzed through the lens of Hans Kruuk's concept of 'surplus killing'. This approach helps explain ¬ß349 of The Gay Science, where Nietzsche elucidates his critique of the framing of evolutionary theory and offers an enticing attitude towards life. This is followed by a discussion of Newton's use of Christianity as a model for his Marxist-Leninist project, along with Nietzsche's perspective of Christianity and an explanation of the master/slave morality in Genealogy. The idea is extended further by looking at modern correlates of the 'knightly aristocratic masters', and by looking at the modern anthropological research of Richard Wrangham and Christopher Boehm that demonstrates the self-domestication of the human species. I claim that understanding this broader picture gives us great insight into modern culture and morality, which Nietzsche described as the Christianization of humankind.

As you might expect given his field of study, he's very thoughtful and delicately treads a difficult line between embracing intellectualism and questioning its value‚Äîhe is an inveterate questioner, after all. Matthew's a funny, sharp person and it was a delight to have him on, and if you disagree you're a Nazi.

title: The Church of Nietzsche with Keegan Kjeldsen ‚òÖ Andrei Vyktor Georgescu Podcast ‚òÖ Episode #5
description:
Keegan Kjeldsen is an author, philosopher and musician who runs the Nietzsche Podcast and makes music with Destroyer of Light. I invited him on the podcast to talk about what it means to have a Nietzschean community,
and more broadly what is involved in building community, what role we can expect to play in society. I find it appropriate that out of all the people to lead the public understanding of Nietzsche through a podcast, it's a musician; he has an understanding of how important it is to *feel* meaning as something that throttles your body, rather than a set of ideas. There's a musical element to Nietzsche, in the sense that he gets under your skin and enchants with his words, he creates compelling characters, images, stories, turns of phrases, ironic jokes, rather than stuff like: hello I am Nietzsche this is what I believe and it is correct.

It didn't go exactly the direction I wanted but it's tricky because as a topic it's so vast; Nietzsche's thought is already so complicated and varied that it takes a lot to unpack. We spent God knows how long just discussing ¬ß40 in The Gay Science, which I wanted to bring up because it's tied to Keegan's attempt at building a secular community that sought dignity for the disdvantaged members of society.

Anyway, after smashing that like and subscribe button, and leaving a hateful, deranged comment, check out Keegan's podcast here:

https://podcasts.apple.com/us/podcast/the-nietzsche-podcast/id1573808070

title: Birth Paean
description:
No, you didn‚Äôt ask to be born‚Äîyou were not so polite. 

Rather, you demanded it in the shape of a shall, your gavel beating the command into bronze.

You harnessed two slaves to build the palace of your body, though not before you did your due diligence.

You lurked and hunted the best you could catch! You were a choosy one indeed; you scouted for the greatest harmony of oculo-facio-skeletal proportions, the plumpest thoughts and bank accounts, the most delectable buttocks, jaws, hips, chests, and feet.

You dissolved the thoughts of your slaves into the acid bath of lust, that most radioactive glow of delight! That substance which swallows all questions and answers into its depth, and makes grumbling victims evince mile-wide smiles.

You affixed yourself to your female slave as if a lamprey, siphoning off nourishment which you commanded from far-off lands; tuna from Thailand, potatoes from Poland, mangoes from Mexico. By air, sea or land you delighted in the armies of servants whose labour was sacrificed for your palace. Once your majestic structure was sturdy enough, you began to explore more land and demand more construction, greater chapels and oratories, greater sacrifices of flora and fauna.

You screamed unintelligibly at your slaves twixt midnight and mid-day, but they understood your meaning‚Äîmore! more! Thus were enlisted indentured servants of all kind at your behest; jesters, cooks, confectioners, tailors, plumbers, nannies, tutors, all for your amusement and nourishment!

Though as your kingdom ages, it seems amnesia has plagued your land. Now, you cloak yourself in a foreign shroud of purity: ‚ÄòI never asked to be born!‚Äô you lament as if a lamb tending its wounds. You forget your bloodied scepter, Your Majesty! You spin yarns; you claim that it was, after all, your slaves who diabolically imprisoned you, that you were an innocent bystander, kidnapped from your slumber!

Fear not, dear king! I remember, we remember: as Nietzsche put it, life itself is essentially appropriation, injury, the conquest of the strange and weak, suppression, severity, obtrusion of peculiar forms, incorporation, and at the least, putting it mildest, exploitation. So rejoice in your palace, dear friend! Enjoy its infinite luster, for it came at an awesome price.
